  <span class="article-tag">Exercise</span>
  <h1>How to Start Exercising (When You've Never Done It)</h1>
  <div class="article-meta">Reviewed by <strong>Sarah Mitchell, BSc Nutrition</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Updated June 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; 8 min read</div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <p>The hardest part of exercise isn't the workout — it's starting. Most beginners try to do too much too soon, get sore or injured, lose motivation, and stop. The evidence-based approach to building a lasting exercise habit looks quite different from what gym culture promotes.</p>
    <div class="highlight-box"><strong>The key principle:</strong> Start embarrassingly easy. A habit you actually do is infinitely more valuable than a perfect programme you abandon after two weeks. Research on habit formation shows that consistency at low intensity beats intensity at low consistency every time.</div>
  </div>

